04866nam a22006015i 9780226243801DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014029026  a9780226243801  a(DE-B1597)524467  a(OCoLC)907924534  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQ183.4.G32bH35 2015 4aQ183.4.G32bH35 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a506.0431848223  aNR 6600qDE-24/20sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/129621:1 aWhitmer, Kelly Joan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Halle Orphanage as Scientific Community :bObservation, Eclecticism, and Pietism in the Early Enlightenment /cKelly Joan Whitmer. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b22 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introducing the Orphanage -- t2. Building a Scientific Community -- t3. Negotiating the Irenical Turn -- t4. Models and Conciliatory Seeing -- t5. An Observator and His Instrument -- t6. Extending the Orphanage -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFounded around 1700 by a group of German Lutherans known as Pietists, the Halle Orphanage became the institutional headquarters of a universal seminar that still stands largely intact today. It was the base of an educational, charitable, and scientific community and consisted of an elite school for the sons of noblemen; schools for the sons of artisans, soldiers, and preachers; a hospital; an apothecary; a bookshop; a botanical garden; and a cabinet of curiosity containing architectural models, naturalia, and scientific instruments. Yet, its reputation as a Pietist enclave inhabited largely by young people has prevented the organization from being taken seriously as a kind of scientific academy—even though, Kelly Joan Whitmer shows, this is precisely what it was. The Halle Orphanage as Scientific Community calls into question a long-standing tendency to view German Pietists as anti-science and anti-Enlightenment, arguing that these tendencies have drawn attention away from what was actually going on inside the orphanage. Whitmer shows how the orphanage’s identity as a scientific community hinged on its promotion of philosophical eclecticism as a tool for assimilating perspectives and observations and working to perfect one’s abilities to observe methodically. Because of the link between eclecticism and observation, Whitmer reveals, those teaching and training in Halle’s Orphanage contributed to the transformation of scientific observation and its related activities in this period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEclecticismzGermanyzHalle an der SaalexHistoryy18th century. 0aEducationzGermanyzHalle an der SaalexHistoryy18th century. 0aObservation (Scientific method)zGermanyzHalle an der SaalexHistoryy18th century. 0aPietismzGermanyzHalle an der SaalexHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencexStudy and teachingzGermanyzHalle an der SaalexHistoryy18th century. 0aSciencezGermanyzHalle an der SaalexHistoryy18th century. 70(DE-588)4045740-00(DE-627)1062005930(DE-576)209066504aPhilanthropismus2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ahalle orphanage, science, enlightenment, pietism, eclecticism, observation, german lutherans, pietists, history, nonfiction, education, class, artisans, nobility, architectural models, botanical garden, bookshop, apothecary, community, scientific method, leibniz, francke, wolff, prussia, politics, natural philosophy, theology, affect, desire, emotion, epistemology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015